As you will see in the [doc][1], there is no `get()` method for a Realtime Database `Reference`. On the other hand, Firestore, the other NoSQL Database offered by Firebase has a [`get()`][2] method. You are probably mixing up the two database services :-)

To read a node in the Realtime Database, you need to use the [`once()`][3] method.

So, in your case you would do as follows:

    exports.getMessage = functions.https.onRequest(async (req, res) =&gt; {
    
        const snapshott = await admin.database().ref(&#39;/messages&#39;).once(&#39;value&#39;);
    
        res.send(snapshott);
    
    });

Two extra things to note:

 1. You can also use the [`on()`][4] method to read a node, but this method is not commonly used in Cloud Functions, since it sets a listener which **continuously** &quot;listens for data changes at a particular location&quot;.
 2. You should manage errors in your Cloud Function, see this official video: https://firebase.google.com/docs/functions/video-series#learn-javascript-promises-pt1-with-http-triggers-in-cloud-functions

  [1]: https://firebase.google.com/docs/reference/node/firebase.database.Reference
  [2]: https://firebase.google.com/docs/reference/node/firebase.firestore.DocumentReference#get
  [3]: https://firebase.google.com/docs/reference/node/firebase.database.Reference#once
  [4]: https://firebase.google.com/docs/reference/node/firebase.database.Reference#on

